    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-21T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-21T10:00:00-05:00" n="757"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d757">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5082: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1"
                            type="from">Wilson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary
                            of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-21T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 21, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 21—1:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>85 [<hi rend="italic">86?</hi>]. For the Acting Secretary from the Secretary.
                    Reference Shanghai’s April 21, 2 p.m. to you.<note n="76" xml:id="d757fn76">From
                        the Minister in China, <ref target="#pg_704">p. 704</ref>.</note> I feel
                    very strongly that if the resolution is adopted by the Committee of Nineteen
                    there should be no reluctance expressed on the part of our Minister and the
                    other Ministers to accept the responsibility which it involves. First it seems
                    to be the only effective way of solving the deadlock in the evacuation. I have
                    never been satisfied with the previous recommendations of the Ministers at
                    Shanghai which seem to me weak. This paragraph of the resolution does not permit
                    the Mixed Commission to set a date for completing the evacuation in advance but
                    merely to state when in their opinion a time has actually arrived in which the
                    Japanese troops can be safely withdrawn. This is a mere finding of fact
                    peculiarly of a nature appropriate for the jurisdiction of such a commission and
                    I think they would be unduly timid to refuse to accede such a
                    responsibility.</p>
                <p>If you agree please notify <persName corresp="#p_JNT1">Johnson</persName>
                    accordingly. [<persName corresp="#p_SHL1">Stimson</persName>.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WHR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
